				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">As a test player a lot of people on test work with the devs and the quality people to try and make eq better, feedback everyone gives is read, every last bit, all bug reports.. You may not feel like it, but it is read.
<br />

<br />
Problem is its very hard for us to use a proper clinical laboatory environment to do our tests on, only SoE can create that, how many times has your best nuke critted for like 128? how often has some nasty mob suddenly started resisting your mana when you were low almost as if to taunt you? So much of it is random, while much seems great on paper, it doesnt always work out..
<br />

<br />
For example, here in the UK if you earn a specific value, you take home say 70% of it after tax, if you earn litterally 1 pound more, you take home... LESS.. yes LESS than you did before, yet, on paper, you earn more..
<br />

<br />
I know there are teams of people doing seemingly pointless tasks, testing the output of things trying to balance others, every person Ive ever spoken to from SoE does play EQ, a few have found time less, but every single one does, some of them are as much a set of addicts as we are. And feel the changes in their game play too.
<br />

<br />
I think it must be hard to please everyone, the casual person doesnt need the same uber pet as the hard core top end gamer, but, as SOE have always shown with their stats, thats just not what the majority of their customers turn out to be. In fact, its always made me laugh the last report I saw said the *average* main was lvl 37.. yes, just 37.. so.. heres a question, why was pop, GoD and OoW targeted for higher audiences?? Even LoY had generally higher stuff than this, its all very confusing.
<br />

<br />
I love OoW, I love my new pet, I love his firey swords. I can finally get some xp that doesnt have me getting my pension before buying a few useful AAs, and while it may not be suitable to all.. I think its certainly a lot better than GoD, and PoP.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
