			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think you'll find that your analysis of the UK tax system is entirely wrong, either that or you've got a completely WHACK government.
<br />

<br />
Here in Australia this is how it works.
<br />

<br />
Making up numbers off the top of my head since I forget exactly what the bracket values are.
<br />

<br />
0-12K - - Tax free
<br />
12K-20K - - 10%
<br />
20K-28K - - 15 %
<br />
28K-35K - - 18 %
<br />
35K-45K - - 25 %
<br />
45K-70K - - 32 %
<br />
70K+ - - 45 %
<br />

<br />
The way the brackets work is that for the *first* 12K, even if you make a trillion billion dollars, you will *not* *ever* pay tax on the first 12K, for the next 8K, (the 12K - 20K bracket) you'll be paying 10 %, and for the next bracet, you'll be paying 15 %.
<br />

<br />
Example:  You are a regular employee making $35K a year, you would pay...
<br />

<br />
12K x 0% + 8K x 10 % + 8K x 15 % + 7K x 18 %, which makes a total of 3260 $ in tax paid over the year.
<br />

<br />
You get a pay rise for becoming a manager, you're now making *drumroll* another 10 dollars a year, $35010, you now pay in tax... 
<br />

<br />
12K x 0% + 8K x 10 % + 8K x 15 % + 7K x 18 % + $10 x 25%, which makes a total of 3262.5 $ in tax paid over the year.
<br />

<br />
The pay rise of 10 dollars gave you a net wage increase of 7.5 dollars for the year.
<br />

<br />
THAT is how a tax system works, I sincerely doubt that europe are stupid enough to run thier tax system on a ridiculous notion of a sea-saw scale, sliding up and down as you approach and break each new tax barrier.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=339789" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://anduran.customer.netspace.net.au/AnduranSig.jpg" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
